HEADWORD: Toupet
<hw>Tou*pet"</hw> <pr>(?;
277)</pr> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>toupet</ets>, dim. of OF. <ets>top</ets> a tuft; of Teutonic
origin, and akin to E. <ets>top</ets>. See <er>Top</er> apex, and cf.
<er>Topet</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A little tuft; a curl or artificial lock of
hair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small wig, or a toppiece of a wig.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her powdered hair is turned backward over a <qex>toupee</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toupettit</ent>⟦br⟧
